<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Town and Country Planning Association</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by TCPA (HOT37)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">About the TCPA</span><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Town and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Country Planning Association (TCPA) is an independent charity working to improve the art and science of town and country planning. The TCPA puts social justice and the environment at the heart of policy debate and inspires government, industry and campaign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers to take a fresh perspective on major issues, including planning policy, housing, regeneration and climate change. Our objectives are to:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Secure a decent, well designed home for everyone, in a human-scale environment combining the best features of town and country </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Empower people and communities to influence decisions that affect them</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improve the planning system in accordance with the princi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ples of sustainable development</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">TCPA r</span><span style="color:#589199; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">esponse</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The TCPA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has chosen to respond solely to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the question </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through leading two Intelligent Energy Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (IEE)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> projects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Association has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> become aware of the vast differences between the UK and other European countries in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the use of community and district heating as well as CHP. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> The positive role of planning in delivering community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">heating</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Planning can play a key role in deli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vering community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Through the work of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">TCPA and Friends of the Earth led </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Planning and Climate Change Coalition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we have explored the ways in which planning policies can support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">community heating and CHP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Our </span><a href="http://www.tcpa.org.uk/pages/planning-for-climate-change-guidance-for-local-authorities-2012.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Planning for climate change - guidance for local authorities</span></a><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which was published following the National Planning Policy Framework in April 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">12, sets out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">best practice policies for plan making and development management, as well as highlighting the importance of evidence gathering. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Lessons from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">an projects</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The TCPA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leads two Intelligent Energy Europe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rojects which bot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h champion the positive role of planning in the delivery of community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heating and CHP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><a href="http://leap-eu.org/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Leadership for Energy Action and Planning</span></a><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (LEAP) has been established to facilitate a network of pan-European municipalities to plan and deliver local sustainable energy solutions in line with the Covenant of Mayors. A partnership of ten organisations from seven European Union (EU) countries have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> come together to improve their capacity as key actors in speeding up the local uptake of sustainable energy measures and the move towards a low-carbon local economy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The project highlights case studies of how local authorities can work in partnership to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> help community groups deliver community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> schemes. The project also focusses on the key role of the Sustainable Energy Action Plan (SEAP) in delivering these objectives.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A recently published </span><a href="http://leap-eu.org/assets/dynamic/publications/56/56.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Case </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Studies Paper</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the LEAP p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roject </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sets out four key recommendations to ensuring greater deployment of decentralized energy, including district heating/ CHP, as follows:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Strong political leadership and support</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Effective and inclusive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cross-departmental working</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Effective and integrated policy frameworks at regional, city and masterplan scales</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Effective and transparent public-private partnerships and funding streams </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The TCPA’s second Intelligent Energy Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> project is </span><a href="http://www.special-eu.org/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Spatial Planning and Energy for Communities In All Landscapes</span></a><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (SPECIAL). The three year project started in March 2013 and focus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on training planners to link spatial planning and energy. Spatial planning and urb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an planners have a pivotal role in developing energy strategies and action plans, and the SPECIAL project has been set up to help bridge the gap between climate change/energy action planning and spatial and urban planning. The project will address the barr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">having a positive and holistic regulatory framework in place, and the importance of creating energy opportunity maps, based on sound evidence bases, which can direct community groups to the most appropriate locations for community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> projects.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the TCPA’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">training for the SPECIAL project </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Association and project partners have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">visited developments in Sweden where district heating is the most common source of heating for apartments and commercial buildings, whilst it is also used fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r detached homes to a lesser extent. During a training week in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the project partnership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">visited the CHP scheme in central Milton Keynes operated by Thameswey Central Milton Keynes Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This exemplified some of the challenges and opportunities of esta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">blishing a district scale CHP scheme in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Set up in 2005, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Milton Keynes scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">required a partnership with English Partnerships (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">now the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCA) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefited from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> being both the planning authority and landowner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It took place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ahead of ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">instream planning policy for district heating in Milton Keynes. However, the Council now has a Core Strategy Policy on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Community Energy Networks and Large Scale Renewable Energy Schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, where it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">promote</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the use of renewable energy schemes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that there will not be any negative social, economic, or environmental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">results from the scheme.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Council also has the following requirements:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1. For developments of more than 100 homes, applications should show that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potential for communi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty energy networks has been explored</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2. For development of more than 200 homes, applications will require community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">energy networks, unless it can be proven that this is not feasible on technical or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic grounds</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3. Regardless of the number of homes in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a proposal, where an existing local energy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">network is established, developments will be expected to connect to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">network, if feasible</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The TCPA believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spatial planning has a key role to play in identifying suitable locations for the installation of dis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trict heating and CHP. Through energy opportunity mapping and heat mapping planners can spatially map demand, capacity and constraints. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the above example illustrates t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hey can also require new developments to consider installing district heating systems,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or require them to connect to existing ones.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Planning and Climate Change Coalition (April 2012) </span><a href="http://www.tcpa.org.uk/data/files/PCC_Guide_April_2012.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.tcpa.org.uk/data/files/PCC_Guide_April_2012.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> LEAP project (2013) </span><a href="http://leap-eu.org/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">ht